defaultPaying for permission work in Judicial Review casesdefault – an adefaultttack on the Rule of Lawdefault 
defaultA large percentage of the Gypsy and Traveller population who live in caravans have to resort to unauthorised encampments due to the lack of adequate sites. If they are faced with a threat of eviction by a local or public authorit
defaulty where the authority concerned are acting unlawfully (e.g. by failing to follow government guidance) then their only recourse is to seek judicial review of the authority concerned.
default The same applies to many other areas of work covered by CLP.
defaultThe first st
defaultage in a judicial review application, once lodged at the court, is that a judge will decide, either on the papers or at an oral hearing, whether the case has sufficient merits and should be given ‘permission’ to proceed to a final hearing. In the consultat
defaultion paper, the government states, with regard to judicial review applications  (at 
defaultpara
default 3.69):
defaultWe propose that providers should only be paid for work carried out on an application for permission (including a request for reconsideration of the application 
defaultat a hearing, the renewal hearing or an onward permission appeal to the Court of Appeal), if permission is granted by the Court.
defaultThis would mean, in a case where the claimant has Legal Aid, that the lawyer (or provider) would have to run the case to a per
defaultmission hearing (if it got that far – see further below) without any guarantee that they would ultimately be paid for the work done. 
defaultJudicial review challenges to local and public authorities are a cornerstone of a democratic society. They allow individu
defaultals to ensure that local and public authorities are prevented from making unlawful decisions or taking unlawful actions. Without such challenges, local and public authorities can act as they please, safe in the knowledge that their actions will not be scru
defaulttinized by the Courts.
defaultMichael Fordham QC has stated:
defaultJudicial review is a central control mechanism of administrative law (public law), by which the judiciary discharge the constitutional responsibility of protecting against abuses of power by public authorities. It constitutes a safeguard which is essential
default to the rule of law: promoting the public interest; policing the 
defaultparameters and duties imposed by Parliament; guiding public authorities and securing that they act lawfully; ensuring that they are accountable to law and not above it; and protecting the rig
defaulthts and interests of those affected by the exercise of public authority power 
default( Judicial Review Handbook, 6
defaultth
default ed., Hart 2012 p5).
defaultIn 
defaultR v Ministry of Defence ex p Smith 
default[1996] QB 517 at 556 D-E, Sir Thomas Bingham MR stated:
default…the court [has] the constituti
defaultonal role and duty of ensuring that the rights of citizens are not abused by the unlawful exercise of executive power.
defaultIn 
defaultR v Secretary of State for the Home Department ex p Fire Brigades Union 
default[1995] 2 AC 513 at 567D-568B, Lord 
defaultMustill
default stated:
defaultTo avoid a
default vacuum in which the citizen would be left without protection against a misuse of executive powers the courts have had no option but to occupy the dead ground…
defaultIn 
defaultRoberts v 
defaultGwyrfai
default DC 
default[1899] 2 Ch 608 at 614, Lindley MR stated:
defaultI know of no duty of the Cou
defaultrt which it is more important to observe, and no power of the Court which it is more important to enforce, than its power of keeping public bodies within their rights.
defaultIn 
defaultR v Inland Revenue Commissioners ex p National Federation of Self-Employed and Small
default Businesses Ltd 
default[1982] AC 617 at 641, Lord 
defaultDiplock
default referred to the 
default“progress towards a comprehensive system of administrative law”
default as 
default“having been the greatest achievement of the English courts in my judicial lifetime.”
defaultAnd now this government intends to 
defaultput judicial review out of reach of everyone apart from the rich. As explained above, the proposal is that Legal Aid providers will not be paid for work done on a judicial review case unless and until permission is granted.  
defaultAt 
defaultpara
default 3.62 of the consultat
defaultion paper the government state that:
defaultWe consider that the appropriate way in which to address this issue is to build into the Civil Legal Aid Scheme a greater incentive for providers to give more careful consideration to the strength of the case before ap
defaultplying for permission for Judicial Review....
defaultWhat is the evidence that Legal Aid providers are not already doing this?  We believe that Legal Aid providers will always give very careful consideration to a matter before they consider lodging a judicial re
defaultview application.
default 
defaultWe would question the evidential basis for this
default defaultassertion
default. defaultThe inference appears to be that practitioners issue judicial review applications frivolously, without having considered the 
defaultpotential merits of such judicial review applications 
defaultand in apparent contempt of well established funding code guidance as to the merits. This inference borders on the offensive. We assert very forcefully  that
default,
default in our experience,  while it cannot always be clear at the outset, practitioners do give proper a
defaultnd careful consideration to the merits of the case, the prospects of success, the remedy sought and the duty to protect the 
defaultL
defaultegal 
defaultA
defaultid 
defaultF
defaultund. It is a balancing act that practitioners are very adept at performing. In addition, there are clear (negative) cost 
defaultimplications of running judicial review applications that have no merit and, as one would expect, such claims are d
defaultealt with very robustly by the 
defaultj
defaultudiciary.
