default“
defaultWell let me give you a raw piece of statistic that will explain the nature of the problem. In 2011, the last year we had figures available, there were 11,359 applications for judicial review. In the end 144 were successful and all of
default the rest of them tied up government lawyers, local authority lawyers in time, in expense for a huge number of cases
default 
defaultof which virtually none were successful. We’re not saying there shouldn’t be judicial
default 
defaultreview, we’re not saying that members of the public a
defaultnd organisations should not be able to challenge public bodies, but what we’re saying is that we have to raise the bar so that we have fewer cases t
defaulthat have no chance of succeeding.
default”
defaultA brief look at the official Ministry of Justice statistics (see table 6
default of the document headed
default 
default“Judicial Review Statistics 2007-2011 – tables”) shows that the Lord Chancellor’s reference to only 144 “successful” cases was misconceived. This is of concern, because it suggests that the Government’s recently announced changes to
default judicial review procedure, and its new proposals for restricting legal aid for judicial review, were based on a misreading of the evidence and/or a misunderstanding of the judicial review process. The Lord Chancellor should, more than anyone, be well awar
defaulte of the constitutional significance of judicial review, as the means by which Government can be held to account by the courts. Restricting access to judicial review – and interfering with the checks and balances of our unwritten constitution – should not 
defaultbe done on the basis of misleading statistics or in an evidential vacuum. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 144 figure relied upon by the Lord Chancellor is false because it only measures the number of judicial review cases that succeeded at a full hearing (as opposed to 212 that fai
defaultled). But PLP’s research suggests that thousands of cases will have settled with a positive outcome for the claimant in 2011: 
default- after the claim was issued but before the permission application was determined 
default- after permission was refused on the papers but before the oral renewal was heard 
default- after permission was granted but before the substantive hearing. 
default…..Research done by PLP and Essex University confirms practitioners’ experience that settled judicial re
defaultview cases are settled favourably to the claimant in a substantial proportion
default defaultof cases
default. 
defaultIt is therefore clear that a substantial proportion of the missing cases and those recorded as withdrawn will have settled on terms favourable to the claimant. 
